Given a sorted array of distinct integers and a target value, return the index if the target is found. If not, return the index where it would be if it were inserted in order.

You must write an algorithm with O(log n) runtime complexity.



code:

class Solution:
    def searchInsert(self, nums: List[int], target: int) -> int:
        for i in range(len(nums)):
            if target==nums[i]:
                return i
            elif target<nums[i]:
                return i  
        return len(nums)   


// This gives time complexity of O(n) .

// Now lets see this in JAVA ---the above approach is Linear Search... or u can say Brute force approach to handle such type of problem 
// Instead of this we can use a better optimal approach to handle this type of problem



class Solution {
    public int searchInsert(int[] nums, int target) {
        int low=0;
        int high=nums.length-1;
        return s(nums,target,low,high,high+1);
    }
    private int s(int[] nums,int target,int low,int high,int ans){
        int mid=(high+low)/2;
        if(high<low)return ans;
        if(nums[mid]==target)return mid;
        else if(nums[mid]>target){
            ans=mid;
            return s(nums,target,low,mid-1,ans);
        }
        else{
            return s(nums,target,mid+1,high,ans);
        }
    }
}



// This approach is called Binary Search and takes O(logn) time complexity to solve such problems ---> divide n conquer technique.
